WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:03.880
I'm Chris Kenny. I'm a PhD candidate at Harvard University.

00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:06.640
And today I'm going to talk to you about how our research team,

00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:10.960
the Alarm Project, uses templates within an R package to structure our

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:14.400
research so that it's in a collaborative and reproducible way.

00:00:15.560 --> 00:00:18.760
Primarily, I'm a political scientist, and what I work on is algorithmic

00:00:18.760 --> 00:00:21.480
redistricting. Now, if you're not familiar with the concept of

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:25.120
redistricting, it's the simple process that's very political and very

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:29.480
argumentative about how you separate a state or region like a county

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:33.439
into different districts so that you control the way that voters

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:37.639
translate their voice into power. And the way that this can look,

00:00:37.799 --> 00:00:40.320
you know, we'll give some red and blue districts, Republican and

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:43.759
Democratic districts. What our research team works on is how we

00:00:43.759 --> 00:00:47.200
generate large samples, thousands and hundreds of thousands of

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:51.680
alternative plans that we can use to evaluate it. Now, our goal in

00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:55.080
this is to use redistricting algorithms to evaluate each state's

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:58.680
redistricting process. So we can look at this and say, this works or

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:02.040
this doesn't, this is gerrymandering, a kind of negative thing that

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:06.120
can happen here. The problem we often run into is that social science

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:10.400
data is extremely messy. This type of data that we're using is coming

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:14.599
from thousands of different people across the United States that often

00:01:14.599 --> 00:01:17.760
are not actually trained to do the things that they're doing, right?

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:21.320
You'll have people that just kind of end up in a job where they run

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:24.279
their whole county's election system and have never considered that

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:29.120
before. So pretty much every place needs manual intervention. To fix

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:33.680
that, we enlist labor, right? We enlist our very smart undergrads who

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:38.320
help us and help us work on this. Now, this introduces our new

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:41.760
problem, which is that undergrads are pretty much by definition

00:01:41.879 --> 00:01:45.599
inexperienced, right? We're trying to push them into doing research

00:01:45.599 --> 00:01:48.800
and they're ambitious, but they need to learn both R packages and

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:52.000
Git and all sorts of other tools. So we want to teach them in a way

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.160
that doesn't overwhelm them. So the particular solution that our team

00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:59.239
has ended up with is to place the project within an R package. And

00:01:59.239 --> 00:02:03.919
I'll make that concrete. So senior members of the team, grad students

00:02:03.919 --> 00:02:08.520
and faculty, set up a simple package. DevTools create just like you

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:13.479
would normally do. And then we set up all of the research tools as if

00:02:13.479 --> 00:02:16.559
it's part of that package. And that includes the project management,

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:20.479
which we'll go into. This means that when your junior members, those

00:02:20.479 --> 00:02:23.960
undergraduates or new grad students set up and want to start using

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:26.520
this, all they have to do is run DevTools load all and they get

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:31.119
everything into their environment. This allows us to set up things that

00:02:31.119 --> 00:02:34.600
require no new tools. And it's going to look very familiar. So if you

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:40.160
see our good old friend RStudio's file explorer, the package stuff is

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:43.440
the normal package stuff. And all we're doing really is adding a few

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:46.720
more folders and a few more functions that let us do the research

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:51.440
stuff. Stuff being the technical word, of course. So what we're really

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:54.520
doing, then, is using the R package to handle all of the project

00:02:54.520 --> 00:02:58.720
management part. And we create a series of functions. So, for example,

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:02.759
if you want to create a new analysis, there's an analysis function. Or

00:03:02.759 --> 00:03:08.000
if you want to set up a pull request on GitHub, we automate that. Things

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.759
like the dataverse, which in the social sciences is a big place to share

00:03:11.759 --> 00:03:16.600
data that you've created. Or because, again, these are inexperienced

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:19.440
people that we're trying to teach how to do research, we want to be able

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:22.520
to peer review their work internally. And so we set up a bunch of

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:26.440
functions that handle that. These can be tested and documented so that

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:29.679
the students don't have to learn anything new. They can just use the

00:03:29.679 --> 00:03:34.199
tools that they're already seeing in their classes. You know, what this

00:03:34.199 --> 00:03:39.199
looks like is if you run into RStudio, you could run something like

00:03:39.199 --> 00:03:43.199
DevTools load all. And then here I'm showing you just running an

00:03:43.199 --> 00:03:48.559
analysis for the state of Delaware, DE, for the 2000 cycle. And when you

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:52.240
hit run, it creates all sorts of files, which is where all of these

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:55.440
templates come in. We can standardize, then, what the inputs are, what the

00:03:55.440 --> 00:04:00.399
outputs. So that little bit of manual intervention doesn't go crazy.

00:04:00.399 --> 00:04:03.520
And, of course, we want to be able to see this and share this. So the other

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:07.240
part of these workflows is to actually validate this. And because our team

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:12.960
uses GitHub, so, for example, for the 2020 Washington analysis, what we

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:17.160
create and set up is an automated set of diagnostics that all they have to

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:22.679
do is copy and paste into GitHub once they're happy with it. And this is

00:04:22.679 --> 00:04:26.440
one of those things that to us works well, but it's not perfect. It's very

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:32.359
flexible and helps the students get in at a very basic level. We develop

00:04:32.359 --> 00:04:36.760
too many R packages as a team. And so it allows us to keep those types of

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:40.679
things updated naturally without using things like our environment. It pairs

00:04:40.679 --> 00:04:45.399
very well with Git. The cons, of course, a determined user can screw it up as

00:04:45.399 --> 00:04:49.880
they please, and it doesn't handle everything. So with that, if you want to

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:54.200
see it in action and see how we use it, you can see our GitHub or send me a

00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:57.880
message on my website. There's a package coming soon.

